instruction:
Review this Go fan-in; it panics with 'close of closed channel'. Explain and fix:

```go
func merge(chs []<-chan int) <-chan int {
	out := make(chan int)
	for _, ch := range chs {
		go func(c <-chan int) {
			for v := range c {
				out <- v
			}
			close(out)
		}(ch)
	}
	return out
}
```

response:
**Bug: every fan-in goroutine closes `out`.** A channel must be closed exactly once. The first goroutine to finish draining its input closes `out`; when a second goroutine finishes and also calls `close(out)`, it panics with `close of closed channel`. Worse, any goroutine still doing `out <- v` after the first close panics with `send on closed channel`. So this races between several illegal operations.

**Fix — close `out` exactly once, after *all* producers are done, using a `sync.WaitGroup`:**

```go
func merge(chs []<-chan int) <-chan int {
	out := make(chan int)
	var wg sync.WaitGroup
	wg.Add(len(chs))
	for _, ch := range chs {
		go func(c <-chan int) {
			defer wg.Done()
			for v := range c {
				out <- v
			}
		}(ch)
	}
	// A single closer goroutine waits for all producers, then closes once.
	go func() {
		wg.Wait()
		close(out)
	}()
	return out
}
```

The pattern: each producer only *sends* (never closes); one dedicated goroutine `wg.Wait()`s for all of them and performs the single `close(out)`. The rules this enforces — *only the sender closes, exactly once, and only when no more sends will happen* — are exactly what the buggy version violated.

